        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Potentia[e] Romanorum prior Scipio viam aperuerat: luxuria[e] posterior aperuit. Paterculus initio libri 2. historia[e] Romana[e]. 
                        Mnemosynon potentia[e], et luxuria[e] Romana[e] ex Paterculo.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
                <book title="Roman History"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                “The first of the Scipios opened the way for the world power of the Romans; the second opened the way for luxury.” Velleius Paterculus, at the 
                beginning of bk. 2 of his Historia Romana. A reminder of Roman power and extravagance from Paterculus.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Thomas Smithus filius solebat dicere, malle se vel ipsa Homerica Iliade carere, qu&agrave;m hac decade Liuiana. Vsq[ue] ad&egrave;o 
                        uarijs vntrinq[ue] mirabilibusq[ue] tam virtutis, qu&agrave;m fortuna[e] actibus capiebatur generosus animus: neutri parti addictus, 
                        sed applaudens pra[e]clari&ugrave;s merenti.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Thomas Smith Junior"/>
                <person name="Homer"/>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                <book title="Iliad"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Thomas Smith junior used to say that he preferred to miss the very Iliad of Homer to missing this decade of Livy. So much was this noble spirit
                captivated by the various remarkable actions of both valor and fortune on both sides. He was not devoted to either party, but applauded the one
                that deserved it more brilliantly.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
